### Summary

In April 2022, Insikt Group acquired and analyzed the latest version of the BlackGuard information stealer that evades previous detections. BlackGuard is an information stealer malware written in .NET that targets victim’s credentials stored on the infected device, including credentials stored in browsers, instant messaging applications, cryptocurrency wallets, VPN, and FTP clients.
On March 11, 2022, Insikt Group analyzed a publicly available sample of BlackGuard stealer’s original version and provided a YARA rule for detections. Since the publication of our YARA rule, BlackGuard authors updated the malware and further obfuscated its code using an obfuscator (Blackberry identified it as Obfuscar; while, de4dot flagged it as .NET Reactor) — both tools are used by threat actors to hinder static malware analysis.
Insikt Group analyzed the updated version of BlackGuard and identified the following functionality:
Ф BlackGuard’s binary includes unnecessary code to slow down analysis
Ф The malware is using anti-analysis and anti-detection techniques implemented either via the malware itself or through the applied .NET obfuscator
Ф BlackGuard is querying “http://ipwhois[.]app/xml/” to determine the victim’s IP address for geolocation purposes and terminates execution if the infected device is located in the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) region
Ф Additionally, the malware checks the infected computer’s geolocation against a list of the CIS countries (a technique o�en employed by Russian-speaking threat actors who claim not to target their home region). In this case, the malware will terminate itself if the infected system is identified as based in Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Moldova, Tajikistan, Uzbekistan, Ukraine, or Russia
Ф Anti-virus checks for products like Sandboxie, 360 Total Security, and COMODO Internet Security, and if found, the malware will terminate itself
Ф Some BlackGuard samples used Telegram as command-and-control (C2); though Telegram is not the only C2 used by this malware family
Ф The malware author is using a GitHub account (https://github[.]com/blackteam1/CheckUPGRADE) to download files and scripts. The most recent update to the GitHub project was on May 4, 2022.
Insikt Group created a YARA rule to detect updated and obfuscated BlackGuard stealer, which can be found attached to this note. Relevant Indicators of Compromise (IOCs) have also been added to this note.
BlackGuard continues to grow in popularity with its operators looking to claim more space on the criminal market of info stealer malware, especially a�er the shutdown of Raccoon stealer, which was one of the top info stealers on the underground.
Below IOCs are SHA256 hashes broken into 2 groups — those with encrypted strings and those without encrypted strings (based on YARA rule validation).
